Title: The Ice Pirates
Description:
Brought to you by the director of Tammy and the T-Rex and Mac and Me.

John Carradine! Anjelica Huston! Ron Perlman!!

Raffill says the film "ended up being a fiasco... MGM went through a transition and they brought in a new guy, who was eventually found out to be stealing money from the company. He was a little problematic sort of a fellow. And he had a bad time with John Foreman so he tried to sabotage the film. Pulled the money out on them, but we did finish it." Raffill says "Turns out the producer was a close friend of Paul Newman's and the studio head had said something derogatory about Paul Newman's wife and so the producer had punched him! ... At the end of the film, they were meant to arrive at Earth and they fly over the beaches of Malibu with everyone swimming in the water and the studio head cut that out! He never told me and it was gone. I had to drink vodka to calm myself down."

Description:
Julia Roberts (a career-focused food writer) tries to break-up her best friend's engagement to a 20-year old college student because (wait for it) she wants him all to herself and for no other reason. She fails in her quest, but her gay best friend flies across the country so she has someone to dance with at the wedding.  ¯\_(ツ)_/¯


Competent direction from Australian indie director P J Hogan lavished on an absolute nothing of a script. Did you know that this, The Joy Luck Club, Waiting to Exhale, How Stella Got her Groove Back, Dangerous Minds, and Rain Man were all written by the same white guy, Ron Bass? And that apparently he had a team of uncredited, mostly female assistants called "The Ronettes" who helped him turn out such a high volume of scripts for and about women? 

This movie is not worth watching, but it low-key changed the way that I think about those mid-budget movies for grownups that we all miss so dearly. It feels like a studio movie from the thirties. It's even padded out with musical numbers. I could kind of imagine what it would be like to be a middle-aged person in the nineties and feel like this was worth the eight-dollar movie ticket.

Title: Shining Through
Description: Ebert: "Imagine this. She is infiltrated into the house of a top Nazi official, as a cook. She botches the meal, serving hot cucumber soup and raw poultry and spilling a dish in a Nazi's lap. She is fired. But another top Nazi immediately offers her a job as the nanny for his children. I know people who couldn't believe “The Hand that Rocks the Cradle” because the nanny wasn't checked out first. Would a Nazi let an unknown person have the run of his house? There's lots of Nancy Drew stuff, as when Griffith discovers the secret room in the Nazi's basement by noticing there are two windows on one side but only one on the other, and there's a hilarious scene in which she flees, frightened, through the city streets in a red opera cloak and a flowing white dress, and of course we get the “friends” who turn out to be enemies (we can tell because their eyes harden), and the escape down the laundry chute, and the convenient plans for the entire Nazi rocket-bomb operation, which she microfilms. But enough."

Title: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band
Description:
Peter Frampton and the Bee Gees sing thru what could have been someone’s acid nightmare of capitalism meets the Beatles. Aerosmith, Earth Wind and Fire, Alive Cooper, Steve Martin, the doctor from John Carpenter’s Halloween and George Burns all play characters named things like “maxwell”, “mr. mustard”, “future villain band” or “billy shears”, and it’s only half as awesome as that sounds. The soundtrack is exactly two songs more tolerable than the film, but the rest of them sound like the golden corral buffet version of sgt pepper and abbey road. Avoid at all costs.  

Before the film's release, Robin Gibb of the Bee Gees announced: "There is no such thing as the Beatles now. They don't exist as a band and never performed Sgt Pepper live in any case. When ours comes out, it will be, in effect, as if theirs never existed."

Title: The Astrologer
Description:
"The film begins by introducing us to Denney as “Craig Marcus Alexander,” who explains via voiceover that he was “born to lie, cheat and steal.” He does this by bilking people out of their money at carnival side shows as an astrologer/fortune teller, but after meeting the love of his life (played by Denney’s real-life cousin, who he repeatedly makes out with), he aims for bigger things by joining a diamond smuggling operation, which he agrees to over an idyllic picnic set in a cemetery. The film then demonstrates one of its first instant classic moments of WTF editing by smash-cutting in the middle of dialog to a prison camp in Africa, where a shirtless Alexander is held prisoner, his diamond mission apparently having gone poorly."

I have seen mere clips of this movie and am, correctly, baffled. But also intrigued???

Title: Drop Dead Fred
Description:
What if your childhood imaginary friend (who was an unhinged, annoying British man) came back to save you from a bad marriage? (And Carrie Fisher was your best friend?)


mj: i want this based off this review: Carl Schroeder wrote: "The imaginary friend is cavortingly rude for a reason; he served to push the girlchild to do mischief for attention and as a cry for help. Now grown up, the woman has forgotten and is about to lose her soul, so events call for some kind of literal return of her demon to force the exposure of her pain. This psychic crisis is poignantly realistic ... the creature who is visible only to the woman is like a poltergeist energy of her repressed self, a problematic ego container into which her powers of assertion and creativity were poured and stored. The movie's resolution is startlingly beautiful."

Title: Laserblast
Description:
u/MovieMike007 on reddit writes: "Now, I’ve seen some pretty fucked up movies in my day but Laserblast was a whole new level of bad, and I’d like to believe that that the script was developed using Boggle tiles and the Daily Word Jumble. The only consistency in the film is that not one bit of it makes any sense, not the beginning nor the middle and not the end. Characters are introduced without any sort of proper backstory or eventual payoff, and it’s clear that veteran actors Keenan Wynn and Roddy McDowall did their work in a single afternoon and were probably paid in sandwiches, and aside from stop-motion effects man David W. Allen, who created the really cool alien turtle dudes, nobody else deserved even that."

ET: Can confirm, very silly.

Title: Trancers 6: Life After Deth
Description:
We open with recut footage of Tim Thomerson acting mildly vexed about having to do another Trancer mission. Cut to title: “300 Years 1 Minute 49 seconds earlier …” We’re introduced to Jack Deth’s daughter, Josephine, who is observing a meteor shower through a telescope in her living room. Jack Deth trancers into her body or whatever, and for the next 80 minutes we get to enjoy the lead actress do her goddamndest to channel Jack Deth—smoking Marlboros, drinking whiskey, wearing cool guy jackets, calling women “toots” and singeing Trancers. All the actors totally suck (although the scientist at the observatory is notably the worst of the bunch and consequently a TREAT), the script is just enough to not be entirely nothing, there are no sets or costumes and the only props are something that appears to be a supersoaker spray painted silver and mounted to a tripod and some flasks filled with jewel-toned science liquids.

From start to startling finish, this is a preposterous slop, and I love it very, very much. -Becca

so many of the critical responses of Sonic take into account that “it’s a video game movie,” but detective pikachu proved you can use video games to tell a real story about people and this is not a real story about people. it’s jim carrey spasmodically scraping the bottom of his early crazed performances bucket, it’s James Marsden seeming way too self aware, and it somehow takes Ben Schwartz’s mania down to nil. 

all in all to say, the overall vibe of the film wasn’t overwhelmingly dull and i laughed every time Marsden spoke free ads for the olive garden. hint: it happens more than once. 

I don't know who wrote the above review, but I can say that it is just and true. - SH

Title: Between Worlds
Description:
Between Worlds follows Joe (Cage), a down-on-his-luck truck driver haunted by the memory of his deceased wife and child. He meets Julie (Potente) a spiritually gifted woman who enlists Joe in a desperate effort to find the lost soul of her comatose daughter, Billie (Mitchell). But the spirit of Joe's dead wife Mary proves stronger, possessing the young woman's body and determined to settle her unfinished business with the living.

Title: Saru no Gundan (SFドラマ 猿の軍団, Army of the Apes)
Description:
This is a Japanese sci fi tv series set over 26 episodes. A scientist named Kazuko Izumi and two young children, Jiro Sakaki and Yurika, mistakenly travel through time to a future, where the planet Earth is now ruled by bad actors who wear non-moving ape masks. The trio struggle to find a way to get back home to the 20th century, with the help of one surviving human, Godo, and his little ape friend, Pepe.

In 1987 an American film producer bought the series and edited the 26 episodes into a tight 94 minute cut. It is insane.

Title: Bad Boys
Description:
Michael Bay's first movie is raw, uncut, kinda-boring Bayhem. 

Every shot is *interesting*, which is as exhausting as it is in later Bay movies, but less stylistically cohesive. Men yell at each other, either because of gay panic or because everyone is hateful. All non-white people are viewed from a white gaze. 

But the weird thing is how much of the movie is, like, a bad screwball comedy, where the married (sexually-frustrated) Martin Lawrence character has to assume the identity of his single, inexplicably rich partner (Will Smith) in order to hold onto a witness (a woman who is definitely not a prostitute who is a replacement witness for the sex worker who was the witness until she was gunned down in front of her). Hilarity doesn't so much ensue as it lends its pacing to unpleasant scenes of people yelling at each other. Just watch The Rock. -SH

Title: Liquid Sky
Description:
Google lists Liquid Sky’s genre as “Sci-fi/Comedy of Manners,” which is not a genre I had considered.

Apparently this was the most successful independent film of 1983, so I’m pretty sure this isn’t actually slop, but it does look super weird.

It appears to be about cocaine, aliens, and the world of high fashion.

Correction: this is about aliens, heroin and a Russian immigrant’s misconstrual of the punk scene as the world of high fashion. This isn’t slop, but it is deeply strange.

Bigtime trigger warning for sexual assault; it forms a large chunk of the plot. Still, I don’t not recommend this.

Title: Ghost
Description:
i know this was the top grossing film of 1990 and made Demi Moore a bankable star, but what i remember most besides the pottery is Whoopi Goldberg playing a straight up con-artist who “accidentally” is able to talk with dead people named Oda Mae Brown. pretty sure there’s loads of casual racism in this. update: this film is basically casual racism the movie ☹️☹️

also Swayze landed the role after he felt his prior two films (road house and next of kin) were too beefy and macho.

Becca: Look, everyone here is acting their hearts out and it’s clear that the production team thought they had a tearjerking classic on their hands. Marvel as increasingly unlikeable Sam Wheat carves a path of destruction through his old life and the life of unwitting psychic sidekick Oda Mae Brown. Gag as the film routinely sidesteps any and all characterization of non-white characters except for Oda, whom Sam bullies into assisting his quest for ghost vengeance by keeping her awake all night singing, Guantanamo-style, forcing her to make herself look like a crazy person in front of his rich wife and former coworkers, teases her with the prospect of four million dollars, sends a murderer to scare the hell out of her and her sisters, wrecks the shit out of her apartment and then literally uses her body to make out with his wife one last time before getting her injured in an attempt to escape the murderer. Then Sam Wheat goes to heaven. I hate this movie.

Title: Southland Tales
Description:
Roger Ebert wrote: "I was dazed, confused, bewildered, bored, affronted and deafened by the boos all around me."

As Kelly posed on the carpet with stars Johnson and Gellar, while Marilyn Manson whisked by, he realized, "We were just walking into a shredder."

"I still don't know what that movie was about," Timberlake has said of the film, in which he played a drug-addled pilot.

Guys this movie was inspired by 9/11.


In near-future 2008, Los Angeles (referred to as "The Southland" by locals) is a city on the brink of chaos overshadowed by the growth of an underground neo-Marxist organization. The film follows the criss-crossed destinies of Boxer Santaros, an action film actor stricken with amnesia; Krysta Now, a psychic ex-porn star in the midst of creating a reality TV show; and twin brothers Roland and Ronald Taverner, whose destinies become intertwined with that of all mankind. The Taverner twins are revealed to be the same person by the engineers of Treer, duplicated when Roland traveled through a rift in space-time, while Boxer has become the most wanted man in the world despite his political ties and his having the fate of the future, in the form of a prophetic screenplay foretelling the end of the world, in his hands.

Title: Color Out of Space
Description: At its core, this takes an H. P. Lovecraft cosmic horror story and enacts it in the present with such literal-mindedness that you can't even tell whether the original had a racist message or just a racist subtext: there's a color where it doesn't belong, and it makes things degenerate. Against this backdrop a family slowly unravels and melts and squooshes. The paterfamilias is Nic Cage, who gives a great freak-out performance which cites earlier freak-outs, like the voice from Vampire's Kiss. Satisfying but gross B-movie, a treat for Cage-Heads. - SH

Title: Blast From the Past
Description:
In 1963 Los Angeles, Christopher Walken and Sissy Spacek mistake a plane crashing into their backyard for “the big one;” a nuclear strike that forces them comically into their well stocked shelter for 35 years. Along the way, they conceive Brendan Fraser and teach him to dance and what baseball is, at least in theory. In 1999, he emerges to retrieve supplies and falls in love with Alicia Silverstone’s Eve character and hijinx ensue. Well, maybe only regular jinx ensues.

Title: Megaville
Description:
So imagine that you saw Total Recall as a kid and it scared the crap out of you and you didn’t understand it and then, 30 years later, without having rewatched Total Recall in the interim, you had a dream that was nothing like Total Recall but filled you with the vague dream-sensation of Total Recall-ness, and then you half-woke up and couldn’t get back to sleep until you wrote the script for Megaville.

Billy Zane is here and he’s not really bothering. The bad guy spends a lot of the movie issuing inscrutable bad guy orders from a hospital bed. There are flashes of this movie wanting to evoke Chinatown, in a similar (but less overt) way to how Overdrawn at the Memory Bank wants to evoke Casablanca, but, let’s be real, Billy Zane ain’t no Raul Julia.

Title: Tremors 4: The Legend Begins
Description:
Tremors, but it's a Western! The guy who isn't Kevin Bacon in the first film is prim East Coast dandy Hiram Gummer investigating a series of strange deaths at his silver mine! What could it be? Graboids, maybe? Who knows!

MJ: This prequel, set 100 years before the events of the first film, seems to be centered around someone saying “what if we did Tremors in the wild west?” While slow and casually racist, the film does return to the real practical effects of the first film. Unfortunately, the series is great because of Bert Grummer and his doomsday prepped knowledge set of survivalism. This film robs the audience of that very luxury, reducing him to “prim east coast dandy.” He spends the first two thirds of the film literally riding bikes and holding horses for others, namely Billy Drago’s slick outlaw. The film is watchable due to it’s awesome third act though, showing grandfather Gummer’s transition from scaredy cat to full on Atlanta Hawks fan.

Title: Tremors 3: Back to Perfection
Description:
Legendary monster-killer Burt Gummer (Michael Gross) has returned to Perfection, Nev., scene of the original attacks by the worm creatures with razor teeth known as graboids. Sure enough, the creatures attack again, only now they're split into graboids, shriekers and a new mutation known as ass-blasters, which are propelled into flight by combustible flatulence. It's up to Burt, Jack Sawyer (Matthew Seth Wilson) and other locals to save their town from destruction.

Chris: This second sequel is meh, returning to Perfection to witness the town struggling to balance being a real town of 14 people and a tourist attraction for yahoos from Bixby or Carson City. This film introduces a second evolution, aptly named the Ass-Blasters, flying and farting killers. Walter’s niece Jodi is great, the kid from the first film is still dead weight, but the “Kevin Bacon-type” here is more of a “Rob Lowe-type.” There’s an albino Graboid they name “El Blanco” who becomes like, Bert’s friend? I don’t know man, this one was tough.

Title: Tremors 2: Aftershocks
Description:
The guy who isn't Kevin Bacon in the first film goes mercenary on those worms' butts. But what's this? They've evolved!?!

This movie cost less than After Last Season.

MJ: The best of the series, and let me explain why. There’s no Kevin Bacon (plus), Fred Ward’s character is old and sad (plus), and the originally subterranean Graboids have begun evolving into Shriekers, who are blind, terrestrial, hermaphroditic hunters. While the Kevin Bacon replacement character is actually the worst, the December - December romance between Ward and Helen Shaver’s scientist is fucking delightful. It’s not the type of romance that films often explore, and it is totally believable given all the setup about how old and lonely Ward has become. The movie never stops delivering, from RC cars loaded with dynamite to Gummer’s gun that literally shoots through everything. There’s also a Chekov’s 150 pounds of military spec meal rations!

Title: Tremors

Title: Conan the Barbarian
Description:
AHHH NOLD. 

Conan the barbarian is a sword and sandal character and set of stories created in 1932. 

In 1978 Paramount Studios invested 2.5 million dollars into a project, a movie to be written in a cocaine and antidepressant haze by Oliver Stone. 

It was then directed by the guy who John Goodman’s character from The Big Lebowski is based on, who promptly rewrote it. A super macho right wing conservative who had not received credit for writing Dirty Harry and Magnum Force

It’s mostly just hero shots of Arnold walking across deserts with music playing, inter spliced with Room-style sex/what Tommy Wiseau imagines intimacy to be scenes. So many tits. 

And then’s there the whole case of the act three snake cult of KKK members following James Earl Jones? What?

Arnold is beautiful, except when he’s goddamned crucified, and then kills a bird with his fucking teeth while being crucified. The world is crazy. This movie is fucking insane, 🥺

Title: Hellboy
Description:
It could be campier, but who wanted this?

Becca: Ew. This movie is gross. It’s like creepy crawlers: hellboy edition fed through a Mortal Kombat emulator. This movie will make you say no and then it will make you keep saying no and then it will make you ask, “who wanted that gross-out old lady puppet to go full exorcist?” Somebody at a production meeting: “We’ll add a spine-cracking sound, it’s gonna be AWESOME, you’ll see you guys. GUYS. Upside-down old lady plastic puppet boobies. That’s what Hellboy needs. That’s what the audience wants. Boy what an artless hack Guillermo Del Toro was. He really biffed that last Hellboy. But us, we’re gonna get it right. White Russians all around, boys, let’s take a fifteen.”

Also Hellboy is King Arthur or King Arthur was a Hellboy? It’s hard to parse.

Tongue-smoke-corpse-ghost-dad monster is a type of monster the creators of this movie felt the need to invent.

Title: Star Trek: The Motion Picture
Description: Wow look I mean that's obviously a horrible title for the first cinematic outing of the Enterprise crew, but I was honestly surprised at how high the score is on this one. To be fair, I've usually fallen asleep before the ship is out of spacedock, so that score could be coming from anywhere. Reliably soporific; can be used in place of Benadryl. I once woke up in the middle of the night to a scene with the Enterprise being flashed through the 2001: A Space Odyssey kaleidoscope and was like, "What the fuck movie is on right now?" That's how seldom I've made it to anything happening in the movie past spacedock, and that scene is basically a flashier spacedock. It's just a bunch of lights and colors and reaction shots of the crew looking uneasy and it goes on for at least as long as spacedock so it put me right back to sleep. It's like they took a shelved script for a 48 minute episode and filled it with orchestral overture and sparkles until it got all distended like James Doohan's tum.

Title: Final Flesh
Description:
A series of non sequitur vignettes set after a nuclear apocalypse. The script was sent to four different bespoke porn production companies, each of whom didn't know there were three other parts to the film or that the whole piece was ultimately an exercise in surrealist satire.

I really wanted to like this based on the premise, but unfortunately the result is a missed opportunity that isn’t for anyone. Whoever made this got too carried away in the power trip of making the actors do and say all the lol-so-random shit he wanted, so even though the result isn’t strictly porn, it’s still represents a simple adolescent fantasy. It doesn’t matter whether the actors and production companies were aware of the auteur’s intent or not. It’s their job to do whatever weird shit the client pays them to do. No subversion of the medium here. A wiser auteur would have sent the production companies four pieces of The Bald Soprano and insisted on no nudity. Now that I’d enjoy.

Title: Cool World
Description:
1992 Brad Pitt gets sucked into a seedy Ralph Bakshi Roger Rabbit ripoff. Ebert: “Cool World is a surprisingly incompetent film.”

Cool World is ugly inside and out. It assaults you in every scene with a bunch of gross characters that rush in from every angle, often for absolutely no reason other than, presumably, to give you a headache. Cool Word is so broadly hateful that "Cool World" now serves to describe any movie that makes you feel physically ill from the amount of disdain it has for the humanity of the viewer. It's like an unwashed duvet cover at a cheap motel.

According to someone on the internet, Cool World started out as an erotic horror film before Kim Basinger came on board and told the producer she wanted to be able to show it to her kids. I wonder if she ever did.
